description.undefined: IoT-F reprensents failures of IoT systems.

comment.undefined: denotes the cause of a failure.
a form of a dysfunction related to an IoTdevice.
A spike fault happens when there is a rapid increase or decrease in the device state.
represents failure cause related to the connectivity.
denotes actions that allows recovering a device from a given failure.
denotes a type of a market IoT device e.g., FIBARO light bulb.
reprensents failure cause related to power e.g, battery level.
happens when a device stops functioning and is un-responsive to external requests.
represents the effects of a failure mode.

historyNote.value: V3.2.1: Introduced saref:PropertyValue to simplify the association of a measure to a property, without always needing it to be a measurement made by a device.

comment.en: Describes the value for a property. The property value is linked to its value expressed as an RDF literal (DP saref:hasValue), optionally to the unit of measurement (OP saref:isMeasuredIn), and optionally to the properties or properties of interest it is a value of (OP saref:isValueOfProperty).

comment.undefined: an outlier failure occurs when a device to report an incorrect state for a very brief period, usually theduration of just 1 poll.
A high variance failure appears when a device’s state fluctuates back and forth more rapidly than the environment dictates.
represents failure cause related to software.
represents failure cause related to the hardware.
A stuck-at failure happens when a device cannot change state, maintaining the same state despite changes in environment or actuation commands.

historyNote.value: V3.2.1: Use SKOS to organize generic classes in taxonomies.

comment.en: Feature kinds allow to describe kinds of features of interest, with common properties having the same value, and common states being the same. An instance of saref:FeatureKind represents an archetype of real world entities, for example to populate product catalogs.

comment.undefined: failure relate to a response by the device that diverges from the desired device state.

historyNote.value: V3.2.1: saref:Device is explicitly a subclass of saref:FeatureOfInterest and s4syst:System.
V3.2.1: definition of saref:Device clarifies it's a real world entity.
V3.2.1: Most axioms on saref:Device were useless and have been deleted.

example.value: Examples of devices are a light switch, a temperature sensor, an energy meter, a water flow meter, and a laundry dryer. A laundry dryer is designed to dry laundry, and to accomplish this task it has a start/stop function.
For example, a washing machine is designed to wash (task) and to accomplish this task it performs a start and stop function.

comment.en: A tangible object designed to accomplish a particular task. In order to accomplish this task, the device performs one or more functions. An instance of saref:Device represents one specific real world entity.

comment.undefined: happens when sensor data may have offset or have a different gain from the ground truth values.
represents failure cause related to the environment.

comment.en: Links a feature kind, a feature of interest, or a property of interest, to a property value.

Links a device to its kind, a feature kind. Kinds of devices describe models of devices, with common properties having the same value, common states being the same, common functions, and common services.
